description.text:
I.Q.B. (I-cube)
The ultimate toddler toy! After shopping around for toys for our son, I was quite disappointed with the price/longevity/challenge of most toys.
There is some cool stuff out there, but most are utterly simplistic and quickly boring and way too expensive.
So I set out to create the coolest toddler toy ever ;-) The basic idea is to create a fancy looking enclosure, add lots of buttons, dials, some LED's, a mic and speaker. Hook them up to a micro-controller and voila a reprogrammable toy. I have been working on multiple aspects at the same time, but I thought it time to start sharing the first part:
The enclosure, a cube made from printed parts and Plexiglas.
While this is not the cheapest option, it will be quite modular during construction and finalizing.
And I expect the end-result to be quite sturdy and up to toddler abuse.
For me this also an excercise of working with Plexiglas again and I was ordering some anyway ;-) I'll update the project as I move along.
Follow instructions at your own risk!
As always, if you don't know what you are doing, don't do it!

Needed parts
  • - (6) Six square pieces of 3mm plexiglas measuring 16 x 16 cm.
  • - (12) Twelve pieces of M3 rod measuring 157mm.
  • - (24) Plenty of M3 nuts or lock-nuts.
  • - (12) Twelve prints of the "Cube rib 130mm" file.
  • - (8) Eight prints of the "Cube Corner Ball" file.
  • - (1) One print of "Corner Cutter" file.
    • Notes Cut some corners Assembly
  • - Take one rib and put a ball on each end, let's call it an Endrib.
  • - Do this once more.
  • - Take one Plexiglas plate and slip two new ribs on opposite edges.
  • - Slide the Endribs onto the remaining edges.
  • - Let's call this an Endplate (see photos)
  • - Put a piece of 157mm threaded rod through each of the ribs on this constructed piece. (So four rods in total used here.)
  • - Repeat the above process with one other plexiglas plate, so you will have two fully assembled Endplates.
  • - Next, put four Cube ribs in one of the previously constructed Endplates.
  • - Now slide in another four plexiglas plates into this assembly. (see photos)
  • - Put on the other Endplate.
  • - Add the final four M3 threaded rods through the last ribs and tighten them with nuts.

This is an updated Barbie laptop; you can now close the lid.
The original Barbie laptop from waityn4jc was at a weird scale; I resized it to my liking and added a hinge to the screen. Screen has also been updated to include a camera and is now the same length as the base of the laptop so it looks nice when folded. Moved house and lost some of the drawers & dividers for my Electronic parts.

If your drawers also go missing, now you can just print some more, with the added option of 1/2/3 divider(s). I made a few different wall thicknesses, so they should print on most 3D printers

Alternatively, if those pesky drawers turn up without dividers, just print a few dividers, it's a lot quicker than a whole drawer too

BGRL-H01A Toilet roll holder. Designed / measured from scratch within 15 min self-imposed time limit. Roll gap is 75mm, roll tube diameter is 26mm. Re-loading is achieved by splaying the unit apart. and it may not work all that well. Two other (better) variants exist - look on my profile page. Wall mount is here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:293978 Version History:
V1 - original

Summery
I designed Customizable Rack, in OpenSCAD, for my own use as a spice rack, but its size and shape can be customized to hold any object with a round cross section eg cans, bottles, test tubes, aerosols etc. Take a look at the sample STL to get an idea of the different forms that can be created.
Because the rack is made up of individual compartments it holds the items, stored in it, very securely, which may be of importance to you, if your thinking putting a rack on something that moves like a cupboard door or inside a vehicle.
The rack is intended for mounting on a vertical surface and is secured by screws.
Screw slots on the back of the rack conceal the screws from view. Once the screws are in place the rack is quick and easy to put up and take down.
NEW FEATURE! for anyone with a duel extruder printer, you can now add decorative stripes to your rack design.
Should you wish to use them, the values currently in the scad file are those I used to create my own spice rack for Sainsburys own brand spice jars (see photos & STL).

Never used OpenScad before?
This Scad file is designed to make it quick and easy for ANYONE to create their own a custom rack. I've made the Scad file as easy as possible to use, so you don’t need to be familiar with OpenSCAD or programming to use it. Just change the values of a few, well labelled, parameters such as Diameter, Height, Number_or_compartments, etc.

If you’re not already familiar with OpenScad check out the video link below, it will give u a very quick overview of the user interface, which is all you need to know for this project. (you might want to jump the first 1:30 min)

www.youtube.com/watch?v=dx06_gcdMck

I would strongly recommend Downloading OpenSCAD rather than trying to using the in-site editor "Customizer" which I have found to have bugs / problems.
OpenSCAD is fee to Download and under 14 MB in size.

Notes:
1) Be aware, that if u make the rack smaller you probably want to scale the screws accordingly or there is a risk that the screw holes might intersect rack compartments.

Updates:
Customizable Rack 02
I've dded decorative option which enables people with duel extruder printers to add stripes to their rack design.
I have also made few small tweaks and fixes.

Customizable Rack 02.1
Has two additional parameters,
back_depth (moves the rack compartments forward away from the wall)
extend (increases the space between compartments)

description.text: s4 stand

This is a remixed version of david crockers differential infrared z probe.
I uploaded the eagle source files, so you can change what ever you like.
I also added the gerber files as a zip file, which i sent to elecrow for manufacturing the pcb (they are super cheap, a buck for a pcb two sided. if you want to order this pcb from elecrow, please use my referral link: http://www.elecrow.com/referral-program/MTgxNjBqMnQ=/ )

I changed the smd ir diodes for regular ones, as you can get them dead cheap. additionally i mount them in a shroud, so they are positioned properly and the wider opening angle does not matter. I also exchanged the big capacitor, with a ceramic smd one.

The pcb is not compatible to the crocker ir board regarding dimensions, so i designed a custom mount for it, but i don't have an e3dv6 mount or anything like that, since i am using a replicator.

BOM:
1 x smd Resistor 3.3kohm 1206
2 x smd Resistor 3kohm 1206
1 x smd Resistor 1kohm 1206
1 x smd Resistor 866ohm 1206
1 x smd Resistor 330ohm 1206
1 x smd capacitor 22uF 1206
1 x smd capacitor 100nF 1206
1 x smd capacitor 1nF 1206
1 x smd inductance 1uH 1206
1 x smd led red 1206
1 x Attiny25-20su
2 x Infrared LED (SFH4550 better a 3mm ir diode you can get them on aliexpress in pairs with photodiodes in a bag of 100)
1x photodiode (the original spec uses a phototransistor, just add a transistor, to the diode if necessary)
1x pcb (have it manufactured at elecrow, or mill it yourself)

Notes:
The photo diode in the schematic has to be reversed, also the printed + and - symbols on the pcb have to be reversed.

The sfh4550 ir diodes have a small opening angle, but you can use any cheap ir diode with the shroud. The shroud only fits 3mm diodes, if you are using the sfh4550, you have to change it.

Angles of the diodes are 56 and 45 degree, as calculated to provide best precision. Trigger height is 4mm

Sorry no images of the printed part.
firmware for programming the attiny is available here:
https://github.com/dc42/OrmerodSensorBoard/tree/master/Firmware/Mini-differential-IR/V1.2

Big thanks to david crocker, for the omerod design.
https://miscsolutions.wordpress.com/mini-height-sensor-board/

PS: you might want to change the 1206 parts for smaller ones, so you can make the pcb smaller, to match the crocker board dimensions.

description.text:
I saw Squid116's CPAP blower on Reddit, and wanted to have it. However, I didn't want to take my CPAP mask down to my workshop where the power supplies were. I wanted to make it have it's own built-in power adapter. But then I didn't want bare wires that could electrocute me as I fumbled around in the morning, so I decided on an enclosure.

Here's what you'll need:

  • 12V 1.5A AC Adapter with 5.5*2.1mm barrel connector
  • 5.5*2.1mm barrel panel mounts
  • 5015 blower fan
  • 2x M4 nuts
  • 2x M4x20 bolts
  • Soldering Iron with solder

For the nuts and bolts, I'd recommend an assortment kit such as this: http://amzn.to/2yAiVqg

I have also added a hose adapter, which will let you attach the hose that goes to the facemask. Without the hose adapter, you can attach the hose that goes to the CPAP machine. This lets you dry either hose.

Wanhao I3

Yes

Wiring

The wiring on this is pretty simple. You could easily add a switch if you wanted, but I'm just going to plug it in on demand. Be sure to thread the wire through the hole in the 3d printed part before you solder it up, otherwise you won't be able to get the barrel connector through the hole for mounting. I made this mistake several times.

You essentially want to solder the +12V (red) to the positive on the barrel connector, and the ground (black) to the negative. To do this, you'll have to check your polarity. The AC adapter I've listed above has it's +12V on the middle pin, and the ground on the barrel outside. On the connector, it's +12V on the short stub, and ground on the longer one. Please use a multimeter or continuity tester to verify this before you plug it in. Don't burn your house down, kids.

Snap on battery cover for Dexcom G4 slim.

This thing allows for battery changes on the Dexcom G4 slim transmitter.

NB. This is version 1, let me know if you think it can be improved.

You'll need DIY skills to cut down (or mill flat) the G4 transmitter leaving 3.9 mm from the flat base.
Then remove old batteries, as per the YouTube video. (Do a search)
Clean the contacts well. I use a small rotating wire brush in a hand held hobby grinder.
I've found there's no need for solder if you spring out the bottom contacts and form the top ones into a curve so that they will be pressed down to contact by the cover.
Put in 2 new SR1120W batteries
Clip on the cover & seal with silicon rubber.

Test the voltage across the 2 contacts as per the Youtube video
Add a bead of silicon to make it waterproof if required, this would need cutting with a blade before the next change.

Subsequent battery changes will just be a matter of unclipping, changing the batteries and clipping the cover back in.

For detailed instructions, follow along as we tweak and mod our Monoprice Select Mini 3D Printer with cheap upgrades to make it into a precision 3D Printing Instrument, on our Hack-a-Day Project page here: https://hackaday.io/project/14823-maximum-3d-printer-bang-for-the-buck

title: Custom Control box for Tevo Black Widow

description.text:
This is an open-air type enclosure for the electronics from the TEVO Black Widow control box or similar printers. It has easy access for adjustments and wiring. Active cooling with the fans directed IN towards the PCB and MOSFET. You also have the ability to control your accessories such as LED lighting and case fans on or off as needed. You can monitor the output volts and amps of the MKS and MOSFET independently. (See "How I Designed This" section for more details).

Be sure to reposition the STL files accordingly in you slicer software for minimal to no support needed for printing.

Minor support clean up, (if you used supports).

I created this design for minimal, if any, support to be needed. Minor clean up may be necessary. M-5 nuts will need to be inserted in to the appropriate wells.

Open Air design control box for 3d- printer.

I wanted a control box with all the "bells and whistles" to replace the sub-standard control box for my Tevo Black Widow. This is an open air design with cable management. The front panel has access for up to four voltage converter, two volt/amp meters, all LCD controls are accessible, and three accessory on/off switches. The PCB and MOSFET mounting boards can accommodate different board configurations such as MKS 1.4 Gen of MKA 1.5 Base boards and different size MOSFETS. The bottom is configured to accommodate the stock PSU or a Meanwell 600.

Also, the back panel is configured for custom cabling with various types of 2, 3, and 4 pin JST connectors. You'll need to make custom cables to use these connectors or simply use the existing cabling run thru the larger openings.

You will need various M-5 and M-3 bolts and nuts for assembly depending on your specific configuration.

title: Welding 3D prints with 3D pen sample for test

description.text:
This is an add-on part for Maxint's Mx SMD Component Strip Holder. The design for this part is also inspired by ssg1712's Manual SMD Soldering Trays.

This add-on is currently designed to accommodate existing unmodified small versions of the Mx Component Holder. The design is such that you can pull out the SMD tape and separate the plastic cover from the cardboard. The peeled tape then sits in the tray area for you to pick and place. The holes on the part align with the holes on the original Mx Component Holder so the entire enclosure can be mounted if you choose.

To print, the part must be oriented with the "tray" facing down and the flaps of the holder facing up. This allows for the part to be printed without supports (assuming your printer can handle an overhang of ~5mm).

The part is currently listed as a work in progress, as I intend to update the design to be compatible with the Thingiverse customizer.

That's my all new ramps enclosure, a little bit bigger than a conventional 3d printed enclosure.
The cover is fixed by 4 m3 or m2 screws (holes must be drilled on the body). Theres some slots for zip ties at the side, so all cables should be well aligned.
The reset button received a tunnel, button is not designed yet, but its very simple. Theres a wing on the side and bottom that should be removed if necessary.
A 40mmx40mmx10mm 12v fan/cooler should be installed on top (outside) of the box for ventilation.
